      <abstract>
        <p id="P1">The most abundant mRNA post-transcriptional modification is <italic>N</italic><sup>6</sup>-methyladenosine (m<sup>6</sup>A) that has broad roles in RNA biology<sup><xref rid="R1" ref-type="bibr">1</xref>-<xref rid="R5" ref-type="bibr">5</xref></sup>. In mammalian cells, the asymmetric distribution of m<sup>6</sup>A along mRNAs leaves relatively less methylation in the 5â² untranslated region (5â²UTR) compared to other regions<sup><xref rid="R6" ref-type="bibr">6</xref>,<xref rid="R7" ref-type="bibr">7</xref></sup>. However, whether and how 5â²UTR methylation is regulated is poorly understood. Despite the crucial role of the 5â²UTR in translation initiation, very little is known whether m<sup>6</sup>A modification influences mRNA translation. Here we show that in response to heat shock stress, m<sup>6</sup>A is preferentially deposited to the 5â²UTR of newly transcribed mRNAs. We found that the dynamic 5â²UTR methylation is a result of stress-induced nuclear localization of YTHDF2, a well characterized m<sup>6</sup>A âreaderâ. Upon heat shock stress, the nuclear YTHDF2 preserves 5â²UTR methylation of stress-induced transcripts by limiting the m<sup>6</sup>A âeraserâ FTO from demethylation. Remarkably, the increased 5â²UTR methylation in the form of m<sup>6</sup>A promotes cap-independent translation initiation, providing a mechanism for selective mRNA translation under heat shock stress. Using Hsp70 mRNA as an example, we demonstrate that a single site m<sup>6</sup>A modification in the 5â²UTR enables translation initiation independent of the 5â² end m<sup>7</sup>G cap. The elucidation of the dynamic feature of 5â²UTR methylation and its critical role in cap-independent translation not only expands the breadth of physiological roles of m<sup>6</sup>A, but also uncovers a previously unappreciated translational control mechanism in heat shock response.</p>
      </abstract>
